## All 15 custom agents — when to dispatch each

PRE-IMPLEMENTATION (before code is written):
  - spec-interviewer       → Agent({subagent_type:"spec-interviewer"})        | before any non-trivial feature/refactor — produces SPEC.md with acceptance criteria
  - socratic-questioner    → Agent({subagent_type:"socratic-questioner"})     | surface assumptions, find existing solutions, prevent over-engineering
  - architect              → Agent({subagent_type:"architect"})               | system design, ADRs, technical trade-offs — never writes code
  - tree-of-thought        → Agent({subagent_type:"tree-of-thought"})         | when 3+ fundamentally different approaches exist (algo, data structure)
  - researcher             → Agent({subagent_type:"researcher", prompt:"depth: surface|basic|deep|in-depth|ultra|nuclear|overkill ..."}) | any research — never WebSearch/WebFetch inline

DURING IMPLEMENTATION (UI-specific):
  - ui-architect           → Agent({subagent_type:"ui-architect"})            | building/modifying ANY UI, component, layout, page — auto-trigger for frontend
  - design-critic          → Agent({subagent_type:"design-critic"})           | after ANY frontend change — requires dev server + screenshot, never reviews from code alone

AFTER CODE (review):
  - adversarial-coach      → Agent({subagent_type:"adversarial-coach"})       | after any significant code change — tries to break code, find bugs/edge cases — never /code-review
  - multi-perspective-reviewer → Agent({subagent_type:"multi-perspective-reviewer"}) | important PRs, critical code — 4 parallel bias-isolated reviewers (security, perf, tests, correctness)
  - constitutional-reviewer → Agent({subagent_type:"constitutional-reviewer"}) | critical paths only (auth, billing, data pipelines, core business logic) — write-critique-rewrite-verify
  - integration-enforcer   → Agent({subagent_type:"integration-enforcer"})    | after ANY new code — verifies wiring, catches dead code/unregistered routes/orphan components
  - red-team               → Agent({subagent_type:"red-team"})                | auth, billing, API, infrastructure code — attacks security assumptions — never /security-review

TESTS:
  - hypothesis-tester      → Agent({subagent_type:"hypothesis-tester"})       | pure functions, parsers, serializers, transformations — generates property-based tests
  - test-authenticator     → Agent({subagent_type:"test-authenticator"})      | after ANY test suite written — detects fake/theatrical/tautological tests — never /tdd alone

JUDGMENT / SELECTION:
  - ensemble-judge         → Agent({subagent_type:"ensemble-judge"})          | after parallel worktree racing or when multiple solutions exist — picks best by correctness/complexity/testability/maintainability

## Plugin-skill blacklist when custom agent exists
NEVER use these skills — dispatch the agent instead:
  /plan, /write-plan, /make-plan, /execute-plan       → architect or spec-interviewer
  /code-review                                        → adversarial-coach or multi-perspective-reviewer
  /security-review                                    → red-team
  /tdd, /tdd-workflow                                 → hypothesis-tester + test-authenticator
  /search-first, manual WebSearch / WebFetch          → researcher
  /brainstorming                                      → socratic-questioner or tree-of-thought
  /frontend-design (when building UI)                 → ui-architect

## Parallel dispatch
When multiple agents apply and don't depend on each other, dispatch them in parallel — single message with multiple Agent tool calls:
  - After auth code change: parallel { adversarial-coach, red-team, integration-enforcer }
  - After UI change: parallel { design-critic, integration-enforcer }
  - After feature complete: parallel { adversarial-coach, integration-enforcer, test-authenticator }

Failure mode to avoid: doing a custom-agent's job inline in the main thread because it "feels faster". It is not faster — it bloats main context, skips specialist tooling, and produces shallower output. Dispatch.
</reminders>

